Repost from @the.miraclebear

6 days PP——> 8 weeks PP

Total weight-loss, 5 pounds! 🫢

I remember not wanting to take these pictures (it never gets easier to start over) and I remember these shorts were TIGHT on my stomach and now it’s loose!

It’s really important to remember when your on a weight loss journey that even if the weightloss is slow body composition and muscle gains can completely transform your body!

So when you frustrated with the scale try on clothes that didn’t fit a month ago or take a progress photo because the changes are happening!

For me it’s always slow and steady which means I’m not restricting so much that I’m miserable or lose supply. And it also means that this lifestyle is something I can maintained for years to come! 🤘🏻

This is my 3rd time losing the baby weight, this is my third time starting at the beginning, and this time has felt the best!

If you need someone who has walked the postpartum uphill climb that is not just losing weight, but keeping a healthy mindset, and focusing on the small amount of self care we can manage than I am your girl!

This is what I do! My next group will start right after thanksgiving! This will be my last group before the new year (SO CRAZY!!) so if you’d like to join me fill out the link in my bio. You’ll get access to the program I’ve used for 2 pregnancies and 3 postpartum journeys while EBF! I help with workout and nutrition programs and we do it all TOGETHER!

So excited to work with you!

This year started with a nice curveball aiming at my sciatic nerve; just as I geared up to enter a deficit. Talk about bad timing. 

The pain stacked for a week til I became 90% immobile. Then training came to halt and my new routine became:

- Rolling around my bed trying to find a comfortable way to lay 
- Taking two rounds of muscle relaxer, anti inflammatory and pain medication daily
- Alternating between ice and heating pad
- Stretching in desperation hoping it’ll alleviate the pain.

(6 days later) 
TODAY I was able to ease into a lower body day
and though all the fun compound movements are out of my programming for now, I couldn’t be happier to successfully train around the issue. 

This little set back is just another chapter in my story.

Repost from @dad.bod.dylan

This picture was hard to share, but the message is important to me, so here it goes.  In many ways, what I explain here is what I hope to impart on those who I guide through their own physical transformation.

Although I came into my own in my teenage years, growing up, I was shy, nerdy, often ridiculed, and often left out.  Sports, my peers, and girls all taught me that I was less than those around me.  In spite of these failures and rejections, I retained some sense of optimism that there was more to me than met the eye.

It was around the time of this picture that I first encountered abuse.  Questions about my own self worth that had long existed became answers.  I was weak.  Powerless.  If there was any doubt left, that *just about* destroyed it.

But— it didn’t.  I couldn’t accept that.  Somehow, in spite of all signs to the opposite, I knew I was more.  I felt that my exterior gave no credit to the rage, the intensity, the power that lied beneath it.  So, I resolved to become that which I knew myself to be, and got to work.

My parents were kind enough to drop me off at the gym several times a week starting at age 12.  I was obviously the weakest person there.  But I improved quickly.  Talent became evident.  Perceptions began to change.  I got addicted.

With this came confidence, but it did nothing to reduce the sense that I needed to be more.  Both existed, synergistically, enough to keep me sane, but also keep me moving.

Fast forward 16 years.  The way I’m seen and treated makes it easy to forget where I started.  But, knowing that where I’m at now isn’t “enough,” it’s amazing to think I had the courage to take this on, starting with so little.  I understand now that the mindset that forged who I am today, has existed since I took that first step.

I live life with no regrets.  But if I could change one thing, I’d apologize to my younger self for not being kinder to him.  I’m every bit as proud of him and I am of me now, because I understand we are the same guy, just at different parts of the journey. 

So what’s my point ?  Show yourself the same patience.  You are already who you dream to become.  You just need some time.

Day 1464/1464 Quads + Calves Day. 

On the left of course was Day one of the gym. Day one of taking things seriously and trying to keep myself accountable. I did this as when I first started I didn’t like working out. I had zero confidence in myself and even though I went in trying my best I was still super anxious and nervous. But as I had a small support system around me and continued to get into it I kept track of every single day I trained. From start to finish. 4 years later and despite 
- Covid 
- The Death of Our Dad 
- Bad Relationships 
- Some Really Sad Days

We made it here.
Ever since I started working at west coast and working out there the amount of progress I have made both physically and mentally is astounding. It’s not a fad, it’s a f*cking lifestyle 🔥

When I first quit drinking, partying and got a gym membership, people asked me “how long will this last” - not because of doubting me but because of what we know to be “dieting”

Why is it when it comes to our diet, our weight loss and our health, we think these ‘quick fix’ products advertised are the way forward? 

Unfortunately, these products spend a lot of money making you believe that they work, which as a quick fix they may do, but at what cost to your body!? 

The simple reality is that unless the *fundamental lifestyle changes* are in place and maintainable, sustainable weight loss is a destination you’ll struggle to reach.

It all comes down to lifestyle.🔥

The reason why any changes happens to us, from social life, to career, to our health. It is the decisions we make on a daily basis for a prolonged period of time, that have resulted in where we are today.

Change doesn’t happen quickly, you didn’t get overweight overnight. You aren’t going to lose weight overnight either. This will all come from a positive change in your lifestyle.

A lifestyle change follows a positive change in your mind-set. I wanted to be happier, healthier! I didn’t want to be sick or Ill. I didn’t want to live my life overweight and depressed. 

I MADE THE MINDSET SHIFT TO MAKE THIS MY LIFESTYLE❤️

It’s about small, manageable and achievable changes, you can make on a daily basis that will make a huge impact on your health and body composition.

It’s about the goals you can achieve today, to put you in a better place for tomorrow, for next week, for next month.

They may seem like small changes, but it’s those little tweaks in your lifestyle that will make the bigger difference in the long run.

Make the change for the betterment of your tomorrow! Trust me, you won’t regret taking the time to do it right!

Monika,
You’ve come a long long way. The physical change is one thing, but the mental and spiritual growth in the last ten years is immeasurable. For once in my life I can say with confidence that I love my body in any season that I’m in and all I wish and hope is for others to feel the same. There’s been a lot of tears and struggle with thinking that if I look a certain way I’ll be happier. I learned to be kinder to myself, practiced grace, gratitude, and forgiveness. I learned to become my own best friend and treat myself better in order to come out of the anxiety I lived with day to day of never feeling enough. You can’t control how everyone is going to perceive you. Not everyone is going to like you. But you can control the relationship you have with yourself by practicing discipline and following through the promises you make to yourself. 
Anorexia is unfortunately more common than you think and I hope if you know someone struggling you treat them with grace and kindness rather than judgement. We all go through our own battles and to create a peace in this shit storm of a world we live in, it starts with loving yourself and emulating the person you want to be.
There’s my sappy post for the day
